I encountered this issue a few days and initially thought it was something on my end, however, am now leaning toward there being a bug with pinvoke in itself.

Here is my situation

I am trying to get the context of a thread (x64) using [GetThreadContext](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/processthreadsapi/nf-processthreadsapi-getthreadcontext) through PInvoke.

Now this function works fine for me when I use a regular IntPtr to refer to the thread handle that but be passed as the `HANDLE` parameter to this function, however, as soon as I change this from an IntPtr to a SafeThreadHandle (personal implementation of a SafeHandle,) the function no longer works and returns error code 998, which I believe is because the alignment of the structure gets messed up some how (under x64 the context structure needs to be aligned on a 16 byte boundary - `DECLSPEC_ALIGN(16)` in C++.)

Note that my SafeHandle implementation works without problem for other functions such as [OpenThread](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/processthreadsapi/nf-processthreadsapi-openthread), [ResumeThread ](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/processthreadsapi/nf-processthreadsapi-suspendthread)and [Suspend Thread](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/processthreadsapi/nf-processthreadsapi-suspendthread).

Also note that this is only a problem when using the context structure as a reference parameter. If I marshal it into unmanged memory and replace `ref Context context` with `IntPtr context`, there is no issue and the function works as expected.

I will post individual definitions of the structures and functions used below, as well as a complete implementation.

**GetThreadContext PInvoke definition**

```csharp
[DllImport("kernel32.dll", SetLastError = true)]
internal static extern bool GetThreadContext(SafeThreadHandle threadHandle, ref Context context);
```

**Context structure definition**

```csharp
